node.text:
This year's #Sandhurst Tom Surdyke Leadership Award winner goes to Cadet Ethan Erickson with The College of Saint Benedict Saint John's University @fightingsaintsbattalion.

The award is named in memory of Cadet Thomas Surdyke who died from injuries sustained while saving the life of a drowning stranger. Surdyke was a member of the Company B4 @b4_buffaloes Sandhurst team his Plebe year.

After a long grueling process, five teams were named the top teams of the Sandhurst Military Skills Competition.  During Sandhurst, 44 teams representing four U.S. service academies and 16 ROTC programs compete against one another in a variety of military related contests.

Congratulations to USMA Black who won the overall competition. The top teams are: 

1. USMA Black @usma_sandhurst 
2. USMA Gold
3. Company F1 @f1.firehouse 
4. University of North Georgia @ungcadets 
5. The College of St. Benedict St. John's University @fightingsaintsbattalion

node.text:
The U.S. Military Academy dedicated a new monument to honor, promote, and preserve the history and contributions of Buffalo Soldiers who served in the Army at West Point during a ceremony Friday. 

From 1907 to 1947, Buffalo Soldiers were assigned to the 9th and 10th Cavalry Regiments at West Point to provide instruction in mounted drill and tactics to the Corps of Cadets that included notable graduates George S. Patton Jr., Dwight D. Eisenhower, Omar N. Bradley, and others who attended the academy during those four decades.

Gifted to the academy by the Buffalo Soldiers Association of West Point, the 10-foot-tall bronze trooper mounted on horseback characterizes the level of horsemanship expertise that was provided to future Army officers. Nationally renowned sculptor Eddie Dixon was commissioned for the piece that bears likeness to retired Staff Sgt. Sanders H. Matthews Sr., a Buffalo Soldier stationed at West Point. Matthews, who founded the Buffalo Soldiers Association of West Point, worked tirelessly to pay tribute to their memory.

Buffalo Soldiers are a global inspiration, and the monument will ensure that their legacy at West Point is revered, honored, and celebrated around the world, and will continue to inspire next generations of cadets. 

U.S. Army photos by John Pellino/USMA PAO

West Point is excited to announce Army General (Ret.) Vincent K. Brooks, Class of 1980, will preside over the dedication of a monument honoring the contributions of the Buffalo Soldiers who served for forty years at the U.S. Military Academy at West Point, New York. The monument is dedicated to the legacy of African American Soldiers who served in the U.S. Army’s 9th and 10th Cavalry Regiments from 1907-1947.

“These Soldiers embodied the West Point motto of Duty, Honor, Country and ideals of the Ar-my Ethic,” said the U.S. Military Academy 60th Superintendent Lt. Gen. Darryl A. Williams. “This monument will ensure that the legacy of Buffalo Soldiers is enduringly revered, honored and celebrated while serving as an inspiration for the next generations of cadets.”

This Saturday, Army football will honor the 10th Mountain Division in their first home game at #MichieStadium against the Western Kentucky Hilltoppers!

The 10th Mountain Division is a light infantry division in the United States Army based at Fort Drum, New York. Originally activated as the 10th Light Division (Alpine) in 1943 at Camp Hale, Colorado, the division was the only unit of its size in the U.S. Army to specialize in fighting in mountainous and arctic conditions, thus earning the division the “MOUNTAIN” tab. Today, the division retains its “mountain” designation for historical purposes and is organized as a light infantry division. "Climb to Glory!"

Tune in on CBS Sports Net to watch the game live, September 11, at 11:30 A.M. ET

U.S. Army photo by SFC Brooks/USMA PAO

Congratulations to Col. David Barnes who was recently recognized as one of the 15 most notable AI leaders by Forbes. Barnes is the outgoing Professor and Deputy Head of the Department of English and Philosophy at the United States Military Academy, Chief AI Ethics Officer, Army’s Artificial Intelligence (AI), Integration Center (AI2C), and author of The Ethics of Military Privatization: The US Armed Contractor Phenomenon.

In addition to his life of service to his country, Col. Barnes' work focuses on how to include more diverse, rigorous, and meaningful conversation surrounding the responsible design, development, and deployment of AI systems among government, industry, and academia. - Forbes

"Much of my work is aimed at operationalizing the AI Principles into Army AI Design and Development, beginning to frame an Army-wide AI Education and Talent Development program, broadening collaborative efforts across government, academe, and industry, and forming AI ethics strategic messaging for Army senior leaders. The Army is committed to the design, development, deployment, and use of AI technologies in accordance with our nation’s values and the rule of law, and it’s an honor to be a part of this important effort.”

node.text:
Meet the 1st Regimental Commander Donovan Hinton, and Command Sgt. Maj. James Bieler

Hinton, a Kinesiology major from Woodbridge, Virginia, chose West Point because he wanted to surround himself with service oriented poeple.

"My goal as First Regimental Commander is to instill the idea of staying on T.O.P. through Team building, Ownership, and Prioritizing the fundamentals. Despite the many clubs and sports cadets are involved in at the Academy, we are all one team with the same responsibilities when we graduate. It’s when we take the time to develop relationships with one another, hold each other accountable, and stress the importance of even the simplest task that we build a strong team of future officers. We become the best versions of ourselves so we can serve others to the best of our ability and I look forward to seeing cadets embody that this year." ~ Donovan Hinton, Class of 2022

Bieler, a Mechanical Engineering major, from Darien, Connecticut, chose West Point for the leadership and wanted to be surrounded by those motivated by fitness, challeneges, and personal development.

"It is my goal this academic year to foster an environment in the regiment where seeking help, mentorship, and leader development is encouraged. I hope to create a culture of positivity and high energy in the regiment. I hope to inspire my peers to fully appreciate the amazing opportunities we have at West Point.” James Bieler, Class of 2022

U.S. Army photos by Cadet Hannah Lamb, Class of 2023
